figgy.title: Add Derivative Health to Health Report

comments.body:
Questions.
1. Should the heading on a resource show page continue to be "Preservation Status: ..."? Or should it maybe be "Resource Health: ..." (values are "Healthy," "In Process," and "Needs Attention")
3. What about the error message that might be stored on a file? Seems like we should use `processing_status` to display "In Process" for the derivatives, and `error_message` to display "Needs Attention"
4. Do we still want the banner display that says "Files Processed: ..." at the top of a page? Do we want the health report to now incorporate that message? It would require an extra click to see it.

Standup decisions:

1. "Health Status"
2. Agreed.
3. Let's have both - the banner has more info and will be the thing that's stopping them from completing the resource.

We received a zip archive containing 21,986 image files from OIT. Unfortunately, the file names do not match those in the tables; MIchael Muzzie did some investigating and discovered an earlier developer had added some complexity:

>Each image in the image_table has the file_name and the book_id and the image_counter fields.
Then each book in the book_table has a book_id and a book_random_id.
The two tables relate to each other via the book_id, and then the uploaded filename got re-saved as book_random_id underscore image_counter underscore underscore then o, d, or t (original, downsize, or thumbnail).

>So the original PrinUL O-123alt.jpg is actually FsJBnas0oKkTfhlk_1__o.jpg
PrinUL O-123alt2.jpg is FsJBnas0oKkTfhlk_2__o.jpg
DSC_0007.JPG is FsJBnas0oKkTfhlk_4__o.jpg
And so onâ€¦

I created a mapping of old names to new and added it to the Husby Data spreadsheet: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1K7o0gOKXOZnrIJxhLlAFPYUvcBWQSiO_7Fw2rJk52Bc/edit?userstoinvite=mdmuzzie@princeton.edu&sharingaction=manageaccess&role=writer#gid=1398527934

Unfortunately, they weren't all mapped. Investigating.
There are duplicate filenames in the image table. In some cases, the same image is mapped to several entries in the book table.  Seems odd.

researchdata.title: Trainings from Libcal Display Wrong Scheduled Time

comments.body:
@VickieKarasic and I looked again at this issue. The config importer https://github.com/pulibrary/researchdata/blob/main/sites/default/config/migrate_plus.migration.event_rss_importer.yml is configured to treat the dates as America/New_York which is how libguides provides them. Drupal is treating the date values as UTC values and converting them to Eastern time. Things we tried.

- The site's default timezone is set to Eastern time, we changed this to UTC to see if that that impacting importing. 
- We removed the importers configuration to treat incoming dates as America/New_York time. 


Neither had any impact. Possible next times.

- [ ] See if we can explicitly tell the rss importer from Drupal's migrate module to NOT convert any dates values 
- [ ] Research the topic further in Drupal's migrate module forums and stack overflow. 
- [ ] Since this worked at one time (the plugin configuration has remained unchanged since 2020) confirm if Springshare ever at one time provided date values in UTC.
deployed to staging successfully 10/5 with Drupal 10.1.5.
